This hearty stout from Arabel is one of the city's major exports, and deservedly so.  best served at cellar temperature (Arabellans sniff at any other way of serving this drink), this stout is heavy and jet black with a dark brown head of foam.

A delicate, slighly sweet wine made from honey, mead is slow to ferment and in scarce supply compared to grape wines or those of other fruits.  Mead from the fantastic honey bees that inhabit the gardens in Neverwinter is said to be the finest in the North.
This heavy dark stout is brewed at The Drunken Kraken in Cantrev Wyngate.
Love of this potent whisky is a common bond between both Northmen and Ffolk.
Although colorless, odorless, and tasteless, water is thirst-quenching and needed for life.  Many city-folk who do not live near a well or river must purchase water from a market.
This bowl contains a hot broth mixed with pieces of meat and assorted vegetables.
Produced from cow's milk, cheese is a delicious food that goes well with a good wine.
This huge side of roasted meat could easily feed several hungry people.
This run-of-the-mill meal isn't the finest fare in Faern, but nourishing and filling nonetheless.

LORE SUCCESS!!! The Tipsy Ludd looks to the casual passer-by like any old village in. However, you know it as a site which Elminster himself visited and met with the then-Laird MacKorart, who told him a local old wives' tale about the fabled (and feared) 'Castle of Skulls' that supposedly lies somewhere along the southern coast of Gwynneth, deep in the heart of the Llyrath forest.
